{"id":"https://genegraph.clinicalgenome.org/r/ca4b2e89-bf62-466d-a59f-fa3b1c5d9c01v1.0","type":"EvidenceStrengthAssertion","dc:description":"The *BRD4* gene encodes a member of the bromo and extra-terminal domain (BET) family of nuclear proteins. It binds to lysine-acetylated histones, non-histone proteins, DNA and RNA, and is of importance in transcription, replication, and DNA repair. In 2018, Olley *et al.* reported four individuals with *de novo BRD4* variants (one multigenic deletion, two frameshift variants and one missense variant). Their clinical features included intellectual disability, Cornelia de Lange syndrome–like appearance, microcephaly, and cardiac malformations (PMID: 29379197). In 2020, Rentas *et al.* reported another individual with suspected Cornelia de Lange syndrome and a *BRD4* missense variant (PMID: 31911672). Multigenic deletions containing the *BRD4* gene have been reported in at least nine individuals with intellectual disability and congenital anomalies, some of whom exhibit a Cornelia de Lange syndrome–like phenotype (PMIDs: 17339581, 19215039, 20570643, 20648052, 21815246, 21994138, 22750323, 30055032, 30302754). Furthermore, three truncating *BRD4* variants (two de novo and one of unknown inheritance) have been reported in large studies of patient cohorts with autism spectrum disorder or developmental disorders, with no additional phenotype information (PMIDs: 31981491, 33057194). This gene-disease relationship is further supported by neurodevelopmental phenotypes in *Brd4* mouse models (PMIDs: 11997514, 26301327, 31292434) and the protein-protein interaction between BRD4 and NIPBL, the major disease gene for Cornelia de Lange syndrome (PMIDs: 29379197, 30796039, 31320616).\n\nIn summary, *BRD4* is definitively associated with autosomal dominant syndromic intellectual disability. This classification was approved by the ClinGen Intellectual Disability and Autism Gene Curation Expert Panel on April 20, 2022 (SOP Version 8).\n","dc:isV